\f0\fs24 \cf0 ## Goal\
\
Extract the software requirements from the RFP and plan a __fully client-side ReactJS demo web application__ that showcases the alarm plan application functionality without any backend, external APIs, or server-side persistence. The demo will use high-quality mock data and browser/local in-memory behavior to simulate the full workflow.\
\
## Extracted Software Requirements\
\
### 1. Core Product Scope\
\
The RFP requests a web application for recording and managing:\
\
- Alarm plans.\
- Operational zones / areas of operation.\
- Approval and release workflows.\
- Alerting devices and alarm groups.\
- Deployment orders.\
- Vehicle changes and dependencies.\
- Operationally relevant additional information.\
- Maintenance/support, documentation, logging, source-code handover, security, and future extensibility.\
\
For the demo app, these will be represented as client-side screens, workflows, mock datasets, and simulated state transitions.\
\
---\
\
### 2. User, Role, and Permission Requirements\
\
The application must support role-based access based on a hierarchy of fire brigade roles and organizational scopes.\
\
Key roles include:\
\
- LWZ employees.\
- EuS / LKS department employees.\
- State fire command leadership.\
- BFK and deputies.\
- AFK and deputies.\
- BFB / AFB radio roles.\
- BFB-EFU / AFB-EFU roles.\
- PBKDT and deputies.\
- Fire chief and deputies.\
- LuN commander / specialist.\
- Secretary.\
- Firefighter.\
- District-level firefighter.\
- Austrian Water Rescue users.\
\
Permission model requirements:\
\
- Read/write access depends on alarm plan category and organizational scope.\
- One person may hold multiple roles.\
- User must select active role/context after login.\
- Permission matrix must be adaptable and extensible.\
- Users can see alarm plans where their own fire department is included, even if they are not the owner.\
\
Demo implementation:\
\
- Mock login / role selector.\
- Permission-aware navigation and action buttons.\
- Simulated scope filtering by fire department, municipality, district, or all Upper Austria.\
\
---\
\
### 3. Authentication Requirements\
\
Production RFP:\
\
- Authentication via existing Keycloak using OpenID Connect.\
- JWT validation in backend.\
- Roles from Keycloak.\
- Organizational scopes through Keycloak group paths/user attributes.\
\
Demo adaptation:\
\
- No real Keycloak or backend.\
- Client-side simulated authentication.\
- Mock users, roles, claims, and organizational scopes.\
- UI should explain where real OIDC/Keycloak integration would occur in production.\
\
---\
\
### 4. Approval and Release Workflow Requirements\
\
The RFP defines a hierarchical approval process for alarm plans and operational zones.\
\
Standard alarm plan workflow:\
\
1. Authorized fire department member creates alarm plan draft.\
2. Fire chief/deputy starts release process once validations pass.\
3. Assigned fire departments and PBKDTs confirm assignments.\
4. AFK checks/forwards.\
5. BFK checks/forwards.\
6. LWZ confirms and transfers to ELS.\
7. Assigned organizations receive notification after transfer.\
\
Required workflow features:\
\
- Draft save/resume.\
- Minimum validation before release.\
- Approval deadline, e.g. two weeks.\
- Auto-approval after missed deadline.\
- Reminder notifications.\
- Confirm/reject buttons.\
- Rejection requires comment.\
- Comments visible in workflow chain.\
- Comment notifications.\
- Restart/reopen approval only for impacted parties when certain changes occur.\
- LWZ can bypass participants.\
- Initiating fire department can cancel approval.\
- Changed items must be highlighted compared with previous version.\
- Pending and completed approvals overview.\
\
Special alarm plan categories:\
\
- LWZ can create draft alarm plans for categories such as motorway, water, and F-KAT.\
- LWZ can assign specific groups/users for editing or review.\
\
Operational zone approval:\
\
- New or changed zones follow PBKDT \uc0\u8594  AFK \u8594  BFK \u8594  LWZ preliminary review.\
- After LWZ acceptance, alarm plan entry is enabled.\
\
Demo implementation:\
\
- Interactive workflow board/timeline.\
- Mock email/notification center.\
- Approval actions update local state.\
- Visual changed-field comparison.\
- Rejection and restart simulation.\
\
---\
\
### 5. Alarm Plan Creation Requirements\
\
Alarm plans must support categories:\
\
- PB: compulsory area.\
- Autob: highway emergency plans.\
- GW: water alarm plans.\
- Railway: alarm plans in track areas.\
- SOAP: special alarm plans for properties.\
- FKAT: firefighting and disaster relief readiness.\
\
Alarm plan contents:\
\
- Operational zones.\
- Incident categories and keywords.\
- Alarm levels.\
- Time references.\
- Fire departments.\
- Vehicles.\
- Units/equipment.\
- Geographical dependencies.\
- Category-specific cover sheets.\
- Configurable information texts/tooltips.\
\
Functional requirements:\
\
- Save draft.\
- Duplicate existing plan into draft.\
- Attach multiple operational zones.\
- Validate coverage completeness.\
- Validate minimum equipment standards.\
- Prevent release if coverage gap exists.\
- Display selected vehicles/equipment summary.\
- Prevent duplicate vehicle assignment within same deployment category where applicable.\
- Allow special per-keyword planning when enabled by LWZ.\
- Minor alarm keywords show notifications but no full alarm plan.\
\
Demo implementation:\
\
- Multi-step alarm plan wizard.\
- Mock validation engine.\
- Equipment coverage summary.\
- Draft/approved/versioned states.\
- Category-specific cover sheet forms.\
\
---\
\
### 6. Operational Zones and Geoviewer Requirements\
\
Operational zones must be visible and searchable based on permissions.\
\
Map/geoviewer requirements:\
\
- Display operational zones.\
- Support common map layers: basemap, OpenStreetMap, OpenTopoMap, \'d6K50, orthophotos.\
- Display fire station and vehicle locations.\
- Show zones without alarm plans with special coloring.\
- Click zone to open valid alarm plan.\
- Search/filter zones by text and metadata.\
- During alarm plan creation, distinguish assigned vs unassigned fire departments/vehicles.\
\
Zone modification requirements:\
\
- Export selected zone in geoformat.\
- Create new zone.\
- Modify existing zone without re-entering alarm plan.\
- Upload `.jpg`, `.png`, `.pdf`, `.geojson`.\
- Free-text change description.\
- LWZ notification after upload.\
- Original and modified zones downloadable during approval.\
\
Demo implementation:\
\
- Client-side map-like panel using static SVG/HTML/CSS or lightweight client map mock.\
- Mock geo layers and markers.\
- File upload UI simulated locally.\
- Zone approval workflow.\
\
---\
\
### 7. Alerting Devices Requirements\
\
The application must allow authorized users to configure alerting devices/groups per fire department/unit and operational category.\
\
Requirements:\
\
- Default time references: always, weekday day, weekday night/weekend/holiday.\
- LWZ administrators can enable advanced time references.\
- Validation prevents under-coverage.\
- Every deployment category must be defined.\
- LWZ can modify/activate time references, deployment categories, and alarm groups globally or per fire department.\
- Selection must support many units/equipment types such as logistics, boats, drones, EFU, air support, hazmat, rescue, etc.\
\
Demo implementation:\
\
- Alerting device matrix screen.\
- Time-reference toggles.\
- Coverage validation warnings.\
- Admin configuration panel.\
\
---\
\
### 8. Deployment Order Requirements\
\
Internal deployment order:\
\
- Defines which vehicles deploy in what order, at what time, at which alarm level, to which zone, and for which incident keyword.\
- Must be configurable by authorized fire department users.\
- Incident keywords can be grouped by fire departments, including time criteria.\
\
External deployment order:\
\
- Generated from alarm plan design for other zones.\
- Display-only.\
\
Demo implementation:\
\
- Internal dispatch ordering screen with drag-and-drop-like ordering controls.\
- External derived view.\
- Mock export/interface preview.\
\
---\
\
### 9. Vehicle Modification Requirements\
\
Vehicle data changes affect alarm plans.\
\
Required behavior:\
\
- Detect new vehicles from data synchronization.\
- Notify owning fire department.\
- Detect removed vehicles.\
- Notify all fire departments whose plans include the vehicle.\
- Suggest replacement vehicles.\
- Show replacement tasks.\
- Validate replacements against minimum requirements.\
- Send accepted changes through interface server to ELS in production.\
- Notify LWZ, PBKDT, AFK, BFK after replacement.\
\
Demo implementation:\
\
- Vehicle changes task center.\
- Simulated sync event.\
- Replacement recommendation and validation.\
- Mock notification log.\
\
---\
\
### 10. Data and Integration Requirements\
\
Production RFP:\
\
- Data stored at state fire brigade command location.\
- Client provides VM/database server.\
- ELS is source for vehicle, equipment, incident keywords, alarm plan groups, email addresses, and other data.\
- Application communicates with ELS only through an independent interface server.\
- Interface server validates all writes before ELS database changes.\
- Staging YES data requires LWZ review before ELS transfer.\
- Staging NO data can be written through interface server without LWZ review.\
- Old invalid alarm plan versions retained for at least 10 years.\
\
Demo adaptation:\
\
- No backend, no database, no API.\
- Mock data stored in TypeScript files and optionally browser localStorage.\
- Interface server represented as an \'93Integration Preview\'94 screen showing staged vs direct transfer behavior.\
- Version history simulated in local state/mock data.\
\
---\
\
### 11. Logging and Audit Requirements\
\
- All user actions that change data must be logged with username and timestamp.\
- Simple views should not be logged.\
- LWZ employees should see last editor or full editing history per menu/item.\
\
Demo implementation:\
\
- Client-side audit log store.\
- Audit timeline visible to LWZ role.\
